a study of the impacts of us copyright legislation on the open access to texts and other cultural works in the public domain siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr centers programs projects education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home research at siepr research project a study of the impacts of us copyright legislation on the open access to texts and other cultural works in the public domain title a study of the impacts of us copyright legislation on the open access to texts and other cultural works in the public domain principal investigator paul david dates september 1 2006 august 31 2010 sponsor the rockefeller foundation one manifestation of the trend towards the strengthening of copyright protections that has been noticeable during the past two decades may be seen in the secular extension of the potential duration during which access to copyrightable materials remains restricted as a result of the licensing terms that copyright owners are able to impose upon would be users of their publications this paper undertakes to quantify one aspect of the law's effect by providing readily understandable measures of the restrictive consequences in the past present and future of the successive modifications that have taken place in the us copyright statutes specifically it presents estimates of the volume and time distribution of published books whose entry into the public domain has been and will be in the future postponed by the lengthened duration of copyright protection stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
